**First Question:**

 1. If the variable is declared outside a function, constructor,  initializer block or similar (method in particular), then that variable is stored by the class it is written into.

```java
    public class Main {
      protected int number=1; //I&#39;m outside a method!
      public static void main(String[] args) {
        //Some stuff...
      }
      public String outsideMethod=&quot;I&#39;m outside a method!&quot;;
    }
```

 3. If the variable is declared in a method, then that variable is local and will be reduced to rubble after the method has completed its execution.
```java
    public class Main {
      public static void main(String[] args) {
        String value=&quot;I&#39;m gonna get obliterated by the garbage collector later!&quot;;
        //Some moments later...
        value=&quot;Goodbye, see you at the other side of the garbage collector.&quot;;
      }
    }
```

**Second Question:**

 1. You can refer to a class&#39;s member variables if they aren&#39;t set to `private` except if it&#39;s a `nested class`, you can take variables made by the parent class even if it&#39;s private!

 2. You can refer to a class&#39;s variable in two ways.

 3. First is statically, that&#39;s if a variable is declared to be `static`. Static means it stays in the memory longer, hence a &quot;bad hog&quot;, a feature loved and hated by many.

```java
public /*or protected*/ static int number=100; //inside class named MyClass.
//Somewhere outside the class...
MyClass.number //access static variable statically.
```

 4. Second is by initializing an `instance` of the object/class.

```java
public /*or protected*/ int number=100;
//Somewhere outside the class...
MyClass classy=new MyClass(...);
classy.number; //access variable by using an instance of the object.
```
 5. I forgot, you can also access them somewhere inside the class they were declared in!
```java
final String lmao=&quot;lol&quot;;
String im_an_empty_string;
public static void main(String[] a) {
  im_an_empty_string=lmao;
}
```

**Others:**

 1. If you don&#39;t know, final variables are var(s) that can&#39;t be changed no matter what.

 2. The JVM optimizes operations with final var(s) by doing the operations in the memory itself! (A.K.A. statically.)

 3. Lastly, don&#39;t worry about memory allocation! Java knows what it&#39;s doing.

 4. Not unless you run out of physical memory and it throws an OOME.

 5. OOME = OutOfMemoryException     P.S. It&#39;s an error that can&#39;t really be caught nicely.

